## PHASE 2 — GDPR SCRUBBER

This is the core USP and a legal requirement. Build and test this **before** wiring up the AI. No other phase should begin until all scrubber tests pass.

### 2.1 Architecture Rule

> **THE SCRUBBER RUNS CLIENT-SIDE, IN THE BROWSER, BEFORE ANY NETWORK REQUEST.**
> Raw teacher input NEVER leaves the user's device. Only the scrubbed text is sent to the API route, which then forwards it to the AI provider. The API route must also never log or store the request body payload.

### 2.2 Important Limitation — Non-Swedish Names

The built-in name list covers common Swedish names from SCB data. It will **not** automatically detect names like Mohammed, Fatima, Hamza, Amir, Zara, Nour, or Yusuf — all of which are common in Swedish classrooms today. To handle this:

1. The UI **must** present a clearly visible "extra names" input field before every generation, where the teacher can add names not in the built-in list.
2. The UI **must** display a warning if capitalized words remain in the scrubbed text that were not replaced — these may be undetected names.
3. The Terms of Service must state clearly that the scrubber is best-effort, and teachers retain responsibility for reviewing output.

This "custom names" feature is **not optional** — it is part of the MVP. The alternative is a tool that silently fails GDPR on a large percentage of real Swedish classrooms.

### 2.3 Scrubber Implementation

